  "local_port": 38376,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are good, low-cost (or free) alternatives to Google Alerts?",
  "response": "If you're looking for effective, low-cost (or free) alternatives to Google Alerts for monitoring the web, social media, or specific content, several tools can meet your needs. Below are some of the best options available:\n\n### 1. **Talkwalker Alerts**\n- **Website:** [Talkwalker Alerts](https://www.talkwalker.com/alerts)\n- **Features:**\n  - Monitors mentions across the web, including news sites, blogs, forums, and social media.\n  - Delivers alerts via email in real-time or as a daily digest.\n  - Allows for advanced search operators to refine alerts.\n- **Pros:**\n  - Free and easy to set up.\n  - No daily limits on the number of alerts.\n- **Cons:**\n  - The interface is less polished compared to some competitors.\n  - May include some irrelevant results.\n\n### 2. **Mention**\n- **Website:** [Mention](https://mention.com/)\n- **Features:**\n  - Monitors the web and social media for keyword mentions.\n  - Provides real-time alerts and comprehensive analytics.\n  - Allows team collaboration and brand management.\n- **Pros:**\n  - Robust monitoring across various platforms.\n  - User-friendly interface with actionable insights.\n- **Cons:**\n  - The free plan is limited to a few alerts and lower data allowances.\n  - Advanced features require a paid subscription.\n\n### 3. **Feedly**\n- **Website:** [Feedly](https://feedly.com/)\n- **Features:**\n  - Aggregates content from RSS feeds, blogs, news sites, and more.\n  - Offers personalized news feeds based on interests and keywords.\n  - Integrates with tools like IFTTT and Zapier for custom alerts.\n- **Pros:**\n  - Free tier available with essential features.\n  - Powerful organization and discovery tools for content.\n- **Cons:**\n  - Not a direct replacement for keyword-based alerts like Google Alerts.\n  - Some advanced features are behind a paywall.\n\n### 4. **IFTTT (If This Then That)**\n- **Website:** [IFTTT](https://ifttt.com/)\n- **Features:**\n  - Allows you to create custom automation workflows (\"Applets\") that trigger alerts based on specific conditions.\n  - Integrates with numerous services, including RSS feeds, social media, and email.\n- **Pros:**\n  - Highly customizable for various monitoring needs.\n  - Free tier covers most basic use cases.\n- **Cons:**\n  - Requires some setup and understanding of automation workflows.\n  - Limited functionality in the free plan compared to paid tiers.\n\n### 5. **Social Mention**\n- **Website:** [Social Mention](http://socialmention.com/)\n- **Features:**\n  - Real-time social media search and analysis.\n  - Tracks mentions across platforms like Twitter, Facebook, YouTube, and more.\n  - Provides metrics such as sentiment, top keywords, and sources.\n- **Pros:**\n  - Completely free to use.\n  - No registration required.\n- **Cons:**\n  - Data can sometimes be limited or delayed.\n  - Interface is quite basic and lacks advanced features.\n\n### 6. **Twilio with Twilert**\n- **Website:** [Twilert](https://twilert.com/)\n- **Features:**\n  - Specifically designed to monitor Twitter for keyword mentions.\n  - Sends alerts via email when your specified criteria are met.\n- **Pros:**\n  - Free for basic Twitter monitoring.\n  - Easy to set up and use for Twitter-specific alerts.\n- **Cons:**\n  - Limited to Twitter; not a comprehensive web monitoring tool.\n  - Advanced features may require a paid plan.\n\n### 7. **Microsoft Bing Alerts**\n- **Website:** [Bing News Alerts](https://www.bing.com/news/alerts)\n- **Features:**\n  - Similar to Google Alerts, allows you to set up notifications for specific keywords.\n  - Integrates with Microsoft services and Cortana.\n- **Pros:**\n  - Free to use.\n  - Simple setup process.\n- **Cons:**\n  - Less comprehensive than Google Alerts in terms of coverage.\n  - Interface and user experience might not be as refined.\n\n### 8. **Visualping**\n- **Website:** [Visualping](https://visualping.io/)\n- **Features:**\n  - Monitors changes on specific web pages and sends alerts when changes are detected.\n  - Useful for tracking updates on competitor websites, news pages, or any static webpage.\n- **Pros:**\n  - Free tier available with limited monitoring frequency.\n  - Easy to use with visual change detection.\n- **Cons:**\n  - Not designed for keyword-based alerts across the web.\n  - Free plan has limitations on the number of monitored pages and frequency.\n\n### 9. **Yahoo! Alerts (via Third-Party Tools)**\nWhile Yahoo! discontinued its native alerts service, some third-party tools and services can still leverage Yahoo's RSS feeds or search to create custom alerts. However, these might require more manual setup and may not be as reliable as dedicated services.\n\n### **Choosing the Right Tool**\n\nThe best alternative depends on your specific needs:\n\n- **For Comprehensive Web and Social Monitoring:** **Mention** or **Talkwalker Alerts** are excellent choices.\n- **For Custom Automation:** **IFTTT** offers flexibility to create tailored alerts across various platforms.\n- **For RSS and Content Aggregation:** **Feedly** is ideal for keeping up with specific websites and blogs.\n- **For Social Media-Specific Alerts:** **Twilert** for Twitter or **Social Mention** for broader social platforms.\n\nMost of these tools offer free tiers, so you can try them out to see which one best fits your requirements before considering any paid upgrades.",
